WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.000
In this talk, I want to give you two things.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:10.640
One, a systematic way to think about building uncertainty visualizations, and two, a taste

00:00:10.640 --> 00:00:13.000
for how to do it using ggdist.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:18.480
ggdist is an R package that extends ggplot2 to provide three additional geometries.

00:00:18.480 --> 00:00:22.480
Each of these is a composite geometry that uses the same underlying framework.

00:00:22.480 --> 00:00:25.719
To understand how to use these, it's really helpful to step back and think about how to

00:00:25.719 --> 00:00:28.219
construct uncertainty visualizations systematically.

00:00:28.219 --> 00:00:32.779
The idea behind ggdist is that first you would derive an uncertainty distribution.

00:00:32.779 --> 00:00:36.160
I don't really care if you're a Bayesian or a Frequentist, it doesn't really matter.

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:40.139
The point is you derive an uncertainty distribution that you can represent in some way that ggdist

00:00:40.139 --> 00:00:45.000
understands, which might be a bunch of samples, it might be a distributional vector, it could

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:48.259
be a number of different things, I'm not going to get into the details of that.

00:00:48.259 --> 00:00:52.400
But if you've derived the uncertainty distribution, what you can then do is map distributional

00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:56.580
properties onto visual channels, which is what ggplot2 calls aesthetics.

00:00:56.580 --> 00:01:00.020
This density plot you have on the left might be taking the density function and mapping

00:01:00.020 --> 00:01:02.779
it onto the thickness of this slab.

00:01:02.779 --> 00:01:06.500
And you combine it with an interval, which might be, say, taking two quantiles and mapping

00:01:06.500 --> 00:01:11.180
them onto the xmin and xmax of the interval subgeometry.

00:01:11.180 --> 00:01:15.260
And this is exactly how ggdist thinks about uncertainty visualization.

00:01:15.260 --> 00:01:19.699
You have stat slab interval, and you're saying I want to map the PDF, so the density function,

00:01:19.699 --> 00:01:21.180
onto the thickness aesthetic.

00:01:21.180 --> 00:01:25.220
You can then play around with different properties, like maybe the orientation of this slab relative

00:01:25.220 --> 00:01:26.459
to the interval.

00:01:26.459 --> 00:01:30.500
You might decide that you want the CDF instead of the PDF, you might decide that you want

00:01:30.500 --> 00:01:34.220
a gradient plot, so you map the density onto the alpha instead of onto the thickness of

00:01:34.220 --> 00:01:35.220
the slab.

00:01:35.220 --> 00:01:41.180
In fact, as of R4.1, ggdist supports the true gradients that have been added to the graphics

00:01:41.180 --> 00:01:42.180
engine.

00:01:42.180 --> 00:01:46.660
So if you output this to, say, an SVG or a PDF, you can zoom all the way in, you'll get

00:01:46.660 --> 00:01:49.860
high quality gradients no matter how far you zoom in.

00:01:49.860 --> 00:01:54.379
We can create a whole variety of different geometries just from this same slab interval

00:01:54.379 --> 00:01:55.379
family.

00:01:55.379 --> 00:01:59.620
ggist provides a bunch of shortcut geometries, but they're all really derived from the same

00:01:59.620 --> 00:02:00.620
core geometry.

00:02:00.620 --> 00:02:04.379
Of course, dots interval and line ribbon are similarly flexible, you can do a bunch of

00:02:04.379 --> 00:02:07.660
cool different things with them, but I don't really have time to get into the details of

00:02:07.660 --> 00:02:09.619
how you would do all of those different things.

00:02:09.619 --> 00:02:14.339
On the other hand, I did promise Twitter that this talk would be like a Twitter thread directly

00:02:14.339 --> 00:02:15.419
into your skull.

00:02:15.419 --> 00:02:18.220
So for the rest of this talk, I'm just going to jump through a whole bunch of different

00:02:18.220 --> 00:02:19.220
fun examples.

00:02:19.220 --> 00:02:22.119
I'm not going to have time to tell you how to do any of them, but hopefully it will whet

00:02:22.119 --> 00:02:24.619
your appetite and you might go and try it out.

00:02:24.619 --> 00:02:25.619
So let's do this.

00:02:25.619 --> 00:02:30.460
All right, so here's an example of visualizing a Poisson distribution using a distribution

00:02:30.460 --> 00:02:32.380
vector from the distributional package.

00:02:32.380 --> 00:02:36.100
It knows that it's a discrete distribution, so it gives you a histogram instead of a density

00:02:36.100 --> 00:02:37.100
plot.

00:02:37.100 --> 00:02:40.580
And it also allows you to, for example, map the probability onto the color, so you can

00:02:40.580 --> 00:02:42.699
get this nice little gradient effect.

00:02:42.699 --> 00:02:44.339
Speaking of gradients, here's a gradient plot.

00:02:44.339 --> 00:02:48.820
This also shows the use of the dodge position from base ggplot with ggdist.

00:02:48.820 --> 00:02:52.500
Maybe you decide that you want to map the CDF onto it, actually this is the complementary

00:02:52.500 --> 00:02:53.500
CDF.

00:02:53.500 --> 00:02:57.820
You can think about this as an infinite number of bar charts with infinitesimal opacity all

00:02:57.820 --> 00:02:59.339
stacked on top of each other.

00:02:59.339 --> 00:03:04.600
Other things that you can do with mapping aesthetics at the sub-slab level.

00:03:04.600 --> 00:03:08.779
So here what we're doing is we're saying, oh, there's a particular region of interest.

00:03:08.779 --> 00:03:12.419
Maybe we're interested in 0, plus or minus 1.5.

00:03:12.419 --> 00:03:15.339
So we just map that region onto a different color.

00:03:15.339 --> 00:03:20.539
ggdist subdivides the geometry and then allows you to actually map colors onto subparts of

00:03:20.539 --> 00:03:21.820
the geometry.

00:03:21.820 --> 00:03:25.539
Speaking of subdividing the slab, here we're actually using the CDF function, essentially

00:03:25.539 --> 00:03:31.179
bending the CDF in order to show 50, 80, and 95% intervals on the color of the slab.

00:03:31.179 --> 00:03:36.460
So this is a nice example of using PDF and the CDF functions together in order to construct

00:03:36.460 --> 00:03:41.940
a geometry that would be difficult to do if you weren't able to use both of them simultaneously.

00:03:41.940 --> 00:03:47.660
Another kind of complex example of multiple functions being mapped onto the slab simultaneously,

00:03:47.660 --> 00:03:51.059
the fill color is actually varying by group.

00:03:51.059 --> 00:03:54.979
And we're using the fill ramp aesthetic, which is an aesthetic within ggdist that allows

00:03:54.979 --> 00:04:01.139
you to independently ramp the color to white as the color gets closer to 0.

00:04:01.139 --> 00:04:04.860
Speaking of doing crazy things with densities, any probabilist will tell you if you start

00:04:04.860 --> 00:04:09.020
taking density functions and transforming them, then you have to correct for the derivative

00:04:09.020 --> 00:04:10.520
of the transformation.

00:04:10.520 --> 00:04:11.940
Here we have a lognormal distribution.

00:04:11.940 --> 00:04:13.500
We look at it on the raw scale.

00:04:13.500 --> 00:04:14.660
It looks lognormal.

00:04:14.660 --> 00:04:18.380
If you plot this on a log scale, it should look like a normal distribution.

00:04:18.380 --> 00:04:22.059
And in fact, it does look like a normal distribution because ggdist figures out the derivative

00:04:22.059 --> 00:04:24.700
and applies the appropriate correction to the density.

00:04:24.700 --> 00:04:26.459
Everyone loves rain cloud plots these days.

00:04:26.459 --> 00:04:28.179
ggdist makes them incredibly easy to create.

00:04:28.179 --> 00:04:32.179
So we're just combining a slab geometry with a dots interval geometry.

00:04:32.179 --> 00:04:37.679
This works because the dots interval geometry in ggdist automatically figures out how big

00:04:37.679 --> 00:04:39.480
the dots need to be in order to fit.

00:04:39.480 --> 00:04:44.140
This makes it really easy to combine the dots geometry with other more complex plot layouts.

00:04:44.140 --> 00:04:47.339
So here, for example, this is what some people call a logit dot plot.

00:04:47.339 --> 00:04:50.779
Anyway, I hope that I've convinced you that there's a lot of cool stuff you can do with ggdist.

00:04:50.779 --> 00:04:53.100
I haven't even really scratched the surface here.

00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:54.899
So please give ggdist a try.

00:04:54.899 --> 00:04:58.339
And for more of the examples from this talk, check out the URL below.

